What are the causes of polarization of Latin Americaâ€™s politics?

Raduan van Velthem Meira

Introduction

The democratic third wave has generated a big political impact in Latin America. The region used to coups and military rule gave room to vibrant democracies with competitive elections and reasonable political and economic stability. It is natural to suppose that this new democratic reality generates an impact in the way the general population identifies itself politically.

This initial research tries to address this issue. We analyze the degree of politicization and polarization in eleven countries of the region: Argentina, Bolivia, Brazil, Chile, Colombia, Ecuador, Mexico, Paraguay, Peru, Uruguay, and Venezuela.

We divided this blog post into four sections. The first is this small introduction. Second, is a brief a theoretical presentation and justification of the use of the data. Third, we will present a fixed effect analysis of the data to better comprehend the trends in the data. Finally, the last section is a conclusion.

The importance of Left and Right

The definition of polarization and politicization is not so trivial as it may appear. Is it feasible to define ideologies in a multidimensional issue space where the set of preferences are so diverse? How can we cope such diversity in a unidimensional continuum of Left and Right?

First, the Left and Right concepts are old and well-known. They are commonly acknowledged as the expression of political preferences. Second, they are vague enough to be able to represent many ideas. Therefore, â€˜Leftâ€™ and â€˜Rightâ€™ are important as self-identification concepts; a way to manifest your political position, identity.

In this scenario, we can divide individuals into two groups. First, the politically indifferent (\(_{R}I_{L}\))1. This is a person which manifesting any ideology does not generate a utility that justifies the cost of taking a stand. The person does not see that taking a political identity as something relevant. Second, the politically eager (\(_{R}R_{L} \ \textrm{or} \ _{L}R_{R}\)). The cases where the individual understand that she receives some utility if she manifests some political identity either â€˜Leftâ€™ or â€˜Rightâ€™.

We aim to use data from the Latinobarometro to assert the degree of polarization in Latin America. To do so, we will use the variable of â€˜self-identification of â€™Left-Rightâ€™. We manipulate this data to indicate that goes from -5 to 5 where -5 is extreme left and 5 is extreme right. We do that with the assumption that the people which have not identify themselves with from -1 to -5 or from 1 to 5 are the non-ideological individuals 2. From this data, we present the model as follow, where \(X_{i}\) is the observations:

\[\begin{align} Y_{1}&=\frac{\Sigma |X_{i}|}{n} \\ Y_{2}&=\sqrt{\frac{\Sigma (X_{i}-\overline{X})^2}{n-1}} \end{align}\]

\(Y_{1}\) is the mean of the absolute value of the `self-identification of Left-Rightâ€™. This means the level of politicization in a given country since is the distance, on average, that the country s from 0 (\(_{R}I_{L}\)). \(Y_{2}\) is the standard error which indicates the degree of ideological polarization in a given country. Both values go from 0 to, approximately, 5.

Although â€˜politicizationâ€™ and â€˜polarizationâ€™ seems, at the first glance, synonymous; they are independent concepts. We can imagine a society made by three individuals illustrated in set A (A=\(\{\)-5,-5,-5\(\}\)). Here the degree of politicization (\(Y_{1}\)) is 5, but the degree of polarization is 0. The set B (B=${\(1,0,-1\)}$), in turn, have a \(Y_{1}\) of only 0.667, but a \(Y_{2}\) of 1. It is possible to have a high politicization and a low and polarization and, vice-versa.

Empirically, it is reasonable to think of societies becoming more or less politicized without changing their degree of polarization. For example, the society as a whole assuming a Leftâ€™s or Rightâ€™s identity. In Latin America, one could say that similar situation might have happened recently with the `Pink tideâ€™, a sequence of left-wing presidents taking power. To put this assumption to a test, we plot the correlation between politicization and polarization:

As we can see, there is a strong correlation between the two. This, on one hand, generate evidence against the assumption of a Latin Americaâ€™s move to the Left. On the other hand, the strong correlation allows us to use polarization as a proxy for polarization (and vice-versa). Therefore, we only use the variable polarization for the rest of this post. There are three different explanatory frameworks we present to understand polarization in Latin America.

First, socio-economic factors. We will use GDP per capita growth (annual %) and Gini. the former analyzes whether the variance of well-being affect polarization and the latter if more unequal or more equal societies are more prone to be polarized. Second, political factors. We will use the data from Polity an ordinal variable where 0 is to non-Left governments, 1 moderate left-wing governments and 2 is radical left-wing governments.The definition of what were the moderate and radical left-wing governments comes from CastaÃ±eda (2006)3. The first allows us to assert the impact of being more or less democratic to polarization; and the second to assert if the recent left-wing governments in Latin America have generated more polarization.

The evolution of Latin Americaâ€™s political polarization

The first question that we must make is if have any trend the political polarization in Latin America:

The graph 02, in fact, is hiding a more complex pattern that goes along with the recent Latin America history. Dividing the period into three moments we see a pendulum behavior that goes along with period before the â€˜pink tideâ€™, the peak of the left-wing governments and the current political and economic crisis:

Hence, we will now present a data panel analysis with the variable for each of the periods to understand what factor better explain polarization in Latin America. First, 1995 to 2001:

This is a moment in Latin America before the peak of the â€˜Pink tideâ€™, mostly ruled by pro-market governments. This, in part, explain the high variance of the variable â€˜Left governmentsâ€™. The only variable with significance is the Gini index, indicating that more unequal societies make them more polarized. Inequality is a very poignant topic in Latin America due to the fact, in the period, was the region with the highest inequality in the world(IMF4). It is reasonable to assume that inequality is one key factor causing polarization in the region.

This is period is the high tide of the â€˜pink tideâ€™. Once again the left governments variable not only is not significant but also have a major variance. This highlight the diversity the way the left governments were interpreted by the population in very distinct ways, opposing the common idea of two lefts in the region. Similarly, the polity variance demonstrates the beginning of decay in the Latin American institutions. Once again, Gini index is the only variable with significant correlation in polarization. Once again it makes us affirm the social and political importance of inequality in Latin America.

finally, the recent years. This is a moment of the burst of the left-wing governments. The current economic and political crisis has lead to the fall of â€˜pink tideâ€™ presidents. Then, makes sense to understand that the polarization is caused by economic factors. Also, we see how the political variable has a massive variance, indicating the political diversity in the region.

The three periods indicate the preponderance of economic factors -, especially Gini - to understand the polarization variations in Latin America. To give more one more input, letâ€™s analyze the panel data for the entire period:

Only the GDP per capita and Gini are significant, indicating the economic preponderance to stimulate the population towards political action in comparison to ideational factors such as party ideology. In addition, this initial data of the topic goes along the arguments presented by Roberts (2015)5 of a change in the political cleavage in the last decade of the twentieth century in Latin America.

Conclusion

This is just an initial data analysis and generates more questions than answers. Nevertheless, it gives some important indications. First, presents that political motivation is under the effects of economic dynamics. Second, indicate that the left-wing governments in Latin America have not generated political leverage to shape the political behavior in the region. Third, the evolution of the Latin American democracies under the â€˜Third Waveâ€™ to become more consolidated have not an impact in the way the societies see themselves politically.

These initial conclusions lead to some puzzles that we expect to deal with in further research. First, If politics have no impact in the societiesâ€™ self-perception of left and right, why we have the â€˜pink tideâ€™? Second, if the societies have not endorsed a more politicized and polarized politics, why the political elite have become more radical in many countries, like Venezuela?
